        <title>Manifold Distributor</title>
        <paragraph>The water enters each sedimentation tank via a manifold distributor from <problematic ids="id3" refid="id2">|ND.SedManifold|</problematic>. The objectives in the design of this pipe are:</paragraph>
        <block_quote>
            <enumerated_list enumtype="arabic" prefix="" suffix=".">
                <list_item>
                    <paragraph>That the water is distributed evenly throughout the tank.</paragraph>
                </list_item>
                <list_item>
                    <paragraph>That the sludge does not settle inside the tube.</paragraph>
                </list_item>
                <list_item>
                    <paragraph>That a linear jet is created that runs along the length of the tank to resuspend the settled sludge, thus keeping the sludge blanket in suspension.</paragraph>
                </list_item>
                <list_item>
                    <paragraph>That the horizontal currents in the tank, which cause a circulation that brings the sediment to the surface at one end, are eliminated.</paragraph>
                </list_item>
                <list_item>
                    <paragraph>Don’t break the flocs with areas of very high energy dissipation at the outputs.</paragraph>
                </list_item>
            </enumerated_list>
        </block_quote>
        <image align="center" candidates="{'*': 'Sedimentation\\Images/one_manifold.png'}" uri="Sedimentation\Images/one_manifold.png" width="250px"></image>
        <paragraph>The water enters the distribution pipe from the inlet channel through a casting sleeve in the channel slab. From there it goes down to the bottom of the tank through a vertical pipe inside the floc hopper which is connected to the horizontal distribution pipe by a 90 degree elbow cast into the slope of the hopper.</paragraph>
        <target refid="heading-difusores"></target>
        <section ids="difusores heading-difusores" names="difusores diffusers heading_difusores">
            <title>Diffusers</title>
            <image align="center" candidates="{'*': 'Sedimentation\\Images/diffuser.png'}" uri="Sedimentation\Images/diffuser.png" width="150px"></image>
            <paragraph>Each outlet hole at the bottom of the inlet manifold has a <problematic ids="id5" refid="id4">|ND.SedDiffuser|</problematic> tube that directs the water jet downward. The lower end of the tubes is stretched in such a way that the tube wall sticks to the two adjacent tubes. The result is a linear jet that runs along the length of the tank to re-suspend the floccules that settle on any cross-section. These “diffuser” tubes also serve another purpose - that of eliminating the horizontal velocity of water exiting the distributor tube, thus fulfilling the fifth objective of the distributor tube design listed above.</paragraph>
            <paragraph>The horizontal part of the distribution tube is supported at each end in such a way that the diffuser ends reach the height of the edge of the curve, but do not stick to the bottom.</paragraph>
